snippet.textDisplay:
See, this is what we need more today in games.
I'm not saying games today are bad (Nintendo is still good) but the soundtracks aren't original. They're either stock music or music from pre-existing artists. Castlevania, Mega Man, and Final Fantasy (original 10) will always be the gods of gaming soundtracks, and more games nowadays need to learn from them.
snippet.textOriginal:

Castlevania, Mega Man, and Final Fantasy (original 10) will always be the gods of gaming soundtracks, and more games nowadays need to learn from them.

snippet.textDisplay: MrPowerer Fair enough, I will say that the music seems way less important nowadays than it used to be tho. Developers, especially triple A ones focus way more on visuals and less on the music and gameplay than they used to, which is fine, but still a little sad. There are still a fair amount of good video game soundtracks that have come out in the past few years but most of them seem to be retro inspired indies.

snippet.textDisplay: Man I got to play Castlevania. I always here about it being one of the best games. Yes I have heard of it since I was a kid in the 80's and 90's. My best friend was a huge fan while my fave game during that time was Mega Man. I still consider Mega Man the most epic of soundtracks in Video game history. And I'm not considering popularity or if people have heared it as a factor.::Yes Super Mario:: prob takes that poll. But Mega Man gets up pumped, psyched, sing along, and make you want to kick ass and still sounds memorable. And I'm reassured its the best cause of all the games I would play as a kid in any system, I still remember my mom in the distance say "I like that song that's playing" while she cleaner or cooked or did whatever, she always had her two cents when a MM tune came on and she don't know jack about videogames or their names.

snippet.textDisplay: Games back then didn't have the budget for elaborate pieces, so they had to use jingles that they could loop multiple times. Some pieces from games these days are really quite memorable and good. Modern Warfare 2 had great orchestral pieces by Hans Zimmer, and I think Mario Galaxy had a good combination of memorable tunes and orchestral quality. Don't let your nostalgia cloud your judgment.

It's true that when you beat a game that lacks e.g. the ability to save and continue, the rush you get is entirely different from beating...well, any game where you basically are guaranteed to succeed eventually.

snippet.textDisplay:
Don't get me wrong. I love RPG's and a game like FFVII (which is a little old by now) needs save points, etc. But the idea of "game over" has disappeared, in a way, and stopped making sense.

Longer games are not better games. I honestly think that Passwords were a more accurate device. The problem is that it easier to design a long, long game with no "re-playability" factor, than a short game which makes you play it again and again.

You can finish TMNT the arcade game in less than 15 minutes.

snippet.textDisplay: I think there was a creativity, even a greatness in old games that's lacking nowadays. Game companies seemed more willing to and invest in good ideas back then. IT'S STORY TIME(Nothing to do in particular with this song, but with MM2): So, recently, I got a friend into the Mega Man series by 'I Can't Defeat Airman', and once we were racing MM2 on a school bus(He was on IPod, I was on DS Flashcart, btw) , because we both live fairly far away from the school, so, someone asked what we were doing, and I said, "We're playing Mega Man 2.", he responded with "Mega Man is for gay people, you should play CoD instead." 
I weep for today's youth..

snippet.textDisplay:
@TheDudeYouHateToMeet  

Right on!  MM 4 is my favorite.  I love Dr. Cossack's castle themes.  Excluding MM1, all of the original 6 are really good games, but I certainly wouldn't put 2 over any of the other ones.  People just obsess over the goddamn metal blade and a few of the games standout tracks.

MM1 = has it's flaws, like wildly varying difficulty.
MM2 = improvement over 1 overall but with some gameplay kinks yet to be worked out.
MM3 - 6 = Hell yes.  And standardized boss health.

snippet.textDisplay:
This is the most overrated song of all time, from the most overrated game of all time. Why do people love MM2 so fucking much?! There are much better Mega Man games out there. 3, 4, and 5 are a million times better.
Maybe it's because I never had this one when I was a kid, so I'm not looking at it through rose coloured glasses.
Plus, it's way too easy for a Mega Man game. Even on "hard" mode, it's still a lot easier than any of the other Mega Man games on the NES.

snippet.textDisplay: @Ciferz = MM2 is the *simplest* of the series, I'll grant you that. But it's tremendously HARD to play well. Factors include Wood Man (dodging Leaf Shield is still one of the things that gets me), Air Man, Quick Man (spazziest, most undodgable boss ever, -and- his level of Force Beam doom), and the Wily Machine with the undodgable bouncy-beam. Crash Man's level can be really hard too, for those who don't know how to manipulate Pipis, and RSJ is by far the toughest "Big Eye" incarnate of the set.

snippet.textDisplay: @TonyTheTGR @mitihiru MM2 is the easiest of the classic series by far, even on hard it's easy. The difficuly didn't decrease constantly, it just jumps from sequel to sequel. MM7 is harder than MM2, e.g. I would NOT start with MM8 as it's a pretty bad game compared to its predecessors. Starting with 2 would be best if you are concerned about difficulty, and after that just play any of them. If you are not concerned  just start with MM1 and go in order. Remember MM1 has no invulnerability frames.

snippet.textDisplay: Because it takes the typical 30 second awesome 8-bit video game theme and manages to stretch all the way past the minute mark. If you look at almost all NES 8-bit tunes, most of them repeat before they hit 30-45 seconds in length. Combine its length with the fact that it's genuinely an amazing progression of notes, and you have yourself one of the most awesome sounding tunes ever put forth by an 8-bit machine.
snippet.textOriginal: Because it takes the typical 30 second awesome 8-bit video game theme and manages to stretch all the way past the minute mark. If you look at almost all NES 8-bit tunes, most of them repeat before they hit 30-45 seconds in length. Combine its length with the fact that it's genuinely an amazing progression of notes, and you have yourself one of the most awesome sounding tunes ever put forth by an 8-bit machine.

snippet.textDisplay: The reason this song is so great is because it manages to be epic and "final," yet also encourages players, pushing them through the challenging stage. Even if this one's the best, almost every Wily theme is like that if you look-- Wily stage 1 from Mega Man in Dr. Wily's Revenge is one of the most underrated songs in the series.
snippet.textOriginal: The reason this song is so great is because it manages to be epic and "final," yet also encourages players, pushing them through the challenging stage. snippet.textDisplay: Yeah, this song does a superb job of truly making you feel like you're storming Skull Castle.  You're fighting your way into a technological fortress, the last bastion of a world-conquering madman with a genius at mechanized mayhem.  If you fail...the world is his.  That's what good final stage songs are supposed to do, and arguably, none does it better than this.

That's what good final stage songs are supposed to do, and arguably, none does it better than this.
